-8451939", "_content": "afterthelastsupper", "author": "83979593@N00"}, {"raw": "The Last Supper", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "3064182-365863659-47396", "_content": "thelastsupper", "author": "83979593@N00"}, {"raw": "Leonardo da Vinci", "machine_tag": 0, "id": "3064182-365863659-297737", "_content": "leonardodavinci", "author": "83979593@N00"}]}, "comments": {"_content": "2"}, "secret": "facb80d2bb", "usage": {"canblog": 0, "canshare": 1, "candownload": 1, "canprint": 0}, "description": {"_content": "New York artist Devorah Sperber works with assistants and art handlers to install <i>After The Last Supper</i>, one of her multi-colored thread-spool installations at the Brooklyn Museum.  \n\nUsing spools of thread, Sperber creates a pixilated, three-dimensional, inverted image of a masterpiece, which appears as a colorful abstract to the naked eye. Once viewed with an optical device, however, the work becomes immediately recognizable as the famous painting, a full-scale recreation of Leonardo da Vinci's <i>The Last Supper</i>. Sperber deconstructs familiar images so that the brain can reconstruct them. \n\n<i>The Eye of the Artist: The Work of Devorah Sperber</i>\nJanuary 26\u2013May 6, 2007\n<a href=\"http://www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/sperber/\">www.brooklynmuseum.org/exhibitions/sperber/</a>"}, "isfavorite": 0, "views": "1161", "farm": 1, "visibility": {"isfriend": 0, "isfamily": 0, "ispublic": 1}, "rotation": 0, "dates": {"taken": "2007-01-16 00:10:27", "lastupdate": "1240791018", "takengranularity": "0", "posted": "1169474554"}, "originalsecret": "facb80d2bb", "license": "0", "notes": {"note": []}, "server": "117", "safety_level": "0", "urls": {"url": [{"type": "photopage", "_content": "http://www.flickr.com/photos/brooklyn_museum/365863659/"}]}, "editability": {"canaddmeta": 0, "cancomment": 0}}, "stat": "ok"}